Chapter 32

3370
06:06:24,950 --> 06:06:30,620
IN WHICH PHILEAS FOGG ENGAGES IN A DIRECT STRUGGLE WITH BAD FORTUNE

3371
06:06:30,620 --> 06:06:36,090
The China, in leaving, seemed to have carried off Phileas Fogg's last hope.

3372
06:06:36,090 --> 06:06:40,020
None of the other steamers were able to serve his projects.

3373
06:06:40,020 --> 06:07:01,690
The Pereire, of the French Transatlantic Company, whose admirable steamers are equal to any in speed and comfort, did not leave until the 14th; the Hamburg boats did not go directly to Liverpool or London, but to Havre; and the additional trip from Havre to Southampton would render Phileas Fogg's last efforts of no avail.

3374
06:07:01,690 --> 06:07:09,330
The Inman steamer did not depart till the next day, and could not cross the Atlantic in time to save the wager.

3375
06:07:09,330 --> 06:07:17,180
Mr. Fogg learned all this in consulting his Bradshaw, which gave him the daily movements of the trans-Atlantic steamers.

3376
06:07:17,180 --> 06:07:23,911
Passepartout was crushed; it overwhelmed him to lose the boat by three-quarters of an hour.

3377
06:07:23,911 --> 06:07:30,500
It was his fault, for, instead of helping his master, he had not ceased putting obstacles in his path!

3378
06:07:30,500 --> 06:07:50,489
And when he recalled all the incidents of the tour, when he counted up the sums expended in pure loss and on his own account, when he thought that the immense stake, added to the heavy charges of this useless journey, would completely ruin Mr. Fogg, he overwhelmed himself with bitter self-accusations.

3379
06:07:50,489 --> 06:07:59,629
Mr. Fogg, however, did not reproach him; and, on leaving the Cunard pier, only said: "We will consult about what is best to-morrow.

3380
06:07:59,629 --> 06:08:00,710
Come."

3381
06:08:00,710 --> 06:08:07,059
The party crossed the Hudson in the Jersey City ferryboat, and drove in a carriage to the St.

3382
06:08:07,059 --> 06:08:09,200
Nicholas Hotel, on Broadway.

3383
06:08:09,200 --> 06:08:21,620
Rooms were engaged, and the night passed, briefly to Phileas Fogg, who slept profoundly, but very long to Aouda and the others, whose agitation did not permit them to rest.

3384
06:08:21,620 --> 06:08:24,639
The next day was the 12th of December.

3385
06:08:24,639 --> 06:08:34,949
From seven in the morning of the 12th to a quarter before nine in the evening of the 21st there were nine days, thirteen hours, and forty-five minutes.

3386
06:08:34,949 --> 06:08:45,559
If Phileas Fogg had left in the China, one of the fastest steamers on the Atlantic, he would have reached Liverpool, and then London, within the period agreed upon.

3387
06:08:45,559 --> 06:08:54,980
Mr. Fogg left the hotel alone, after giving Passepartout instructions to await his return, and inform Aouda to be ready at an instant's notice.

3388
06:08:54,980 --> 06:09:04,370
He proceeded to the banks of the Hudson, and looked about among the vessels moored or anchored in the river, for any that were about to depart.

3389
06:09:04,370 --> 06:09:17,890
Several had departure signals, and were preparing to put to sea at morning tide; for in this immense and admirable port there is not one day in a hundred that vessels do not set out for every quarter of the globe.

3390
06:09:17,890 --> 06:09:24,190
But they were mostly sailing vessels, of which, of course, Phileas Fogg could make no use.

3391
06:09:24,190 --> 06:09:39,890
He seemed about to give up all hope, when he espied, anchored at the Battery, a cable's length off at most, a trading vessel, with a screw, well-shaped, whose funnel, puffing a cloud of smoke, indicated that she was getting ready for departure.

3392
06:09:39,890 --> 06:09:47,500
Phileas Fogg hailed a boat, got into it, and soon found himself on board the Henrietta, iron-hulled, wood-built above.

3393
06:09:47,500 --> 06:09:53,489
He ascended to the deck, and asked for the captain, who forthwith presented himself.

3394
06:09:53,489 --> 06:10:04,410
He was a man of fifty, a sort of sea-wolf, with big eyes, a complexion of oxidised copper, red hair and thick neck, and a growling voice.

3395
06:10:04,410 --> 06:10:05,680
"The captain?"

3396
06:10:05,680 --> 06:10:06,860
asked Mr. Fogg.

3397
06:10:06,860 --> 06:10:08,630
"I am the captain."

3398
06:10:08,630 --> 06:10:11,420
"I am Phileas Fogg, of London."

3399
06:10:11,420 --> 06:10:14,820
"And I am Andrew Speedy, of Cardiff."

3400
06:10:14,820 --> 06:10:17,120
"You are going to put to sea?"

3401
06:10:17,120 --> 06:10:18,620
"In an hour."

3402
06:10:18,620 --> 06:10:20,180
"You are bound for--"

3403
06:10:20,180 --> 06:10:20,979
"Bordeaux."

3404
06:10:20,979 --> 06:10:22,780
"And your cargo?"

3405
06:10:22,780 --> 06:10:23,869
"No freight.

3406
06:10:23,869 --> 06:10:25,380
Going in ballast."

3407
06:10:25,380 --> 06:10:27,319
"Have you any passengers?"

3408
06:10:27,319 --> 06:10:28,970
"No passengers.

3409
06:10:28,970 --> 06:10:30,450
Never have passengers.

3410
06:10:30,450 --> 06:10:31,919
Too much in the way."

3411
06:10:31,919 --> 06:10:34,210
"Is your vessel a swift one?"

3412
06:10:34,210 --> 06:10:37,090
"Between eleven and twelve knots.

3413
06:10:37,090 --> 06:10:39,360
The Henrietta, well known."

3414
06:10:39,360 --> 06:10:43,220
"Will you carry me and three other persons to Liverpool?"

3415
06:10:43,220 --> 06:10:44,640
"To Liverpool?

3416
06:10:44,640 --> 06:10:46,320
Why not to China?"

3417
06:10:46,320 --> 06:10:48,170
"I said Liverpool."

3418
06:10:48,170 --> 06:10:49,550
"No!"

3419
06:10:49,550 --> 06:10:50,570
"No?"

3420
06:10:50,570 --> 06:10:51,420
"No.

3421
06:10:51,420 --> 06:10:55,349
I am setting out for Bordeaux, and shall go to Bordeaux."

3422
06:10:55,349 --> 06:10:57,440
"Money is no object?"

3423
06:10:57,440 --> 06:10:58,220
"None."

3424
06:10:58,220 --> 06:11:03,310
The captain spoke in a tone which did not admit of a reply.

3425
06:11:03,310 --> 06:11:07,480
"But the owners of the Henrietta--" resumed Phileas Fogg.

3426
06:11:07,480 --> 06:11:11,420
"The owners are myself," replied the captain.

3427
06:11:11,420 --> 06:11:14,090
"The vessel belongs to me."

3428
06:11:14,090 --> 06:11:16,440
"I will freight it for you."

3429
06:11:16,440 --> 06:11:18,000
"No."

3430
06:11:18,000 --> 06:11:20,000
"I will buy it of you."

3431
06:11:20,000 --> 06:11:21,460
"No."

3432
06:11:21,460 --> 06:11:28,110
Phileas Fogg did not betray the least disappointment; but the situation was a grave one.

3433
06:11:28,110 --> 06:11:35,670
It was not at New York as at Hong Kong, nor with the captain of the Henrietta as with the captain of the Tankadere.

3434
06:11:35,670 --> 06:11:39,919
Up to this time money had smoothed away every obstacle.

3435
06:11:39,919 --> 06:11:42,520
Now money failed.

3436
06:11:42,520 --> 06:11:55,660
Still, some means must be found to cross the Atlantic on a boat, unless by balloon--which would have been venturesome, besides not being capable of being put in practice.

3437
06:11:55,660 --> 06:12:04,239
It seemed that Phileas Fogg had an idea, for he said to the captain, "Well, will you carry me to Bordeaux?"

3438
06:12:04,239 --> 06:12:07,379
"No, not if you paid me two hundred dollars."

3439
06:12:07,379 --> 06:12:10,070
"I offer you two thousand."

3440
06:12:10,070 --> 06:12:11,549
"Apiece?"

3441
06:12:11,549 --> 06:12:12,980
"Apiece."

3442
06:12:12,980 --> 06:12:15,910
"And there are four of you?"

3443
06:12:15,910 --> 06:12:17,260
"Four."

3444
06:12:17,260 --> 06:12:20,079
Captain Speedy began to scratch his head.

3445
06:12:20,079 --> 06:12:30,120
There were eight thousand dollars to gain, without changing his route; for which it was well worth conquering the repugnance he had for all kinds of passengers.

3446
06:12:30,120 --> 06:12:36,670
Besides, passengers at two thousand dollars are no longer passengers, but valuable merchandise.

3447
06:12:36,670 --> 06:12:41,420
"I start at nine o'clock," said Captain Speedy, simply.

3448
06:12:41,420 --> 06:12:44,220
"Are you and your party ready?"

3449
06:12:44,220 --> 06:12:50,519
"We will be on board at nine o'clock," replied, no less simply, Mr. Fogg.

3450
06:12:50,519 --> 06:12:52,559
It was half-past eight.

3451
06:12:52,559 --> 06:12:56,760
To disembark from the Henrietta, jump into a hack, hurry to the St.

3452
06:12:56,760 --> 06:13:08,980
Nicholas, and return with Aouda, Passepartout, and even the inseparable Fix was the work of a brief time, and was performed by Mr. Fogg with the coolness which never abandoned him.

3453
06:13:08,980 --> 06:13:12,870
They were on board when the Henrietta made ready to weigh anchor.

3454
06:13:12,870 --> 06:13:22,030
When Passepartout heard what this last voyage was going to cost, he uttered a prolonged "Oh!"

3455
06:13:22,030 --> 06:13:25,710
which extended throughout his vocal gamut.

3456
06:13:25,710 --> 06:13:33,519
As for Fix, he said to himself that the Bank of England would certainly not come out of this affair well indemnified.

3457
06:13:33,519 --> 06:13:43,940
When they reached England, even if Mr. Fogg did not throw some handfuls of bank-bills into the sea, more than seven thousand pounds would have been spent!

3458
06:13:43,940 --> 06:13:47,240
End of Chapter 32

